Now I have the exact interface. Here's what `ExtensionContext` provides:

```typescript
export interface ExtensionContext {
    ui: ExtensionUIContext;
    mode: ExtensionMode;
    hasUI: boolean;
    cwd: string;
    sessionManager: ReadonlySessionManager;
    modelRegistry: ModelRegistry;
    model: Model<any> | undefined;  // ← CAN BE UNDEFINED
    isIdle(): boolean;
    signal: AbortSignal | undefined;
    abort(): void;
    hasPendingMessages(): boolean;
    shutdown(): void;
    getContextUsage(): ContextUsage | undefined;
    compact(options?: CompactOptions): void;
    getSystemPrompt(): string;
}
```

So `ctx.model` IS a property but it's `Model<any> | undefined` — it can be undefined! And `ctx.modelRegistry` exists.

The issue is in `runSubagent`:
```typescript
let model;
if (specialist.model) {
    const [provider, id] = specialist.model.split("/");
    model = getModel(provider, id);
} else if (parentCtx?.model) {
    model = parentCtx.model;
}
// model could be undefined here!
```

When `parentCtx.model` is undefined, `model` stays undefined, and then `createAgentSession({ model: undefined, ... })` likely crashes.

The fix is:
1. If `parentCtx.model` is undefined, try to get a default model from the registry
2. Or use the model registry to resolve a model

Let me check what `ModelRegistry` provides.

